<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-341-060  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 341 060.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  June 5 1989 v6 n22 p62(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Systems integration to flourish in '90s, study says. (AutomationResearch Corp.'s study 'Plantwide Systems Integration')</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ballou, Melinda-Carol.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Automation Research Corp's study titled 'Plantwide SystemsIntegration' indicates that US manufacturers, competing with oneanother and with international companies, will look increasinglyto systems integrators to automate their plants and implementtheir systems.andP;  The study also reports that the US systemsintegration market was valued at $2.8 billion in 1988 and isexpected to grow at a yearly rate of more than 18 percent through1993.andP;  The message of the report is US manufacturers have nochoice but to automate, then integrate because their survival isat stake.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Automation Research Corp. (reports).andO;Topic:     StudyReportsManufacturingForecastingComputer Systems IntegratorsAutomationIndustry Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Projected U.S. market for systems integration. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Systems Integration To Flourish in '90s, Study SaysandM;U.S.andP;  manufacturers competing with one another and with internationalcompanies will look increasingly to systems integrators to automate theirplants and implement their systems, according to a study, &quot;Plantwide SystemsIntegration,&quot; published by Automation Research, a market research company inMedfield, Mass.andM;The U.S.andP;  market for systems integration (SI) was worth $2.8 billion lastyear and is expected to grow at a yearly rate of more than 18 percent through1993, bringing the SI market to more than $6.4 billion by 1993, the studysaid.andM;Global manufacturing competition will be more intense during the 1990s, thestudy said, with a united Europen Economic Community after 1992, alreadyentrenched Japanese companies and increasingly strong plants in developingnations such as Korea, Taiwan and Mexico.andM;U.S.andP;  manufacturers have no choice--they must automate, then integrate, theirsystems because their survival is at stake, according to the study.andM;&quot;We have come a long way compared to five years ago [in automation andsystems integration] .andP;  .  .  but we need to go much further.andP;  Japan andEurope are much more automated than U.S.andP;  plants,&quot; said Andrew Chatha,president of Automated Research.andM;&quot;Other countries have invested quite a bit to have more flexible plants--tobe able to make different products on the same assembly line--and automationis key to flexibility,&quot; Chatha said.andP;  &quot;Tou absolutely need automated plantsthat can be easily changed or programmed to manufacture something different.&quot;andM;In addition to global competition, the international growth of the SI marketis influenced by the need for flexibility and more complex plant operations.andO;Other factors include newer technologies for plantwide integration, such asManufacturing Automation Protocol, distributed relational databases and Xwindows as the basis for a standard user interface over a variety ofapplications, the study said.andM;&quot;More and more users will go out for independent systems integrators--eitherto [computer] vendors or to systems integrators--because they don't have theexpertise or the manpower to implement it themselves,&quot; Chatha said.andM;&quot;DEc, specifically, has been spending a lot of money in building up theirsystem-integration expertise,&quot; Chatha said.andP;  &quot;We estimate that last year DECgenerated $20 million from this business, and I think you're going to see DECtaking on turnkey responsibility for big projects in the future.andP;  Two yearsago, they hardly had anything [in this market].&quot;andM;Other analysts agreed about DEC's place in the market as compared with othercomputer vendors.andM;&quot;There is no question that DEC wants to be a systems integrator--they won a[million-dollar] contract with Boeing and are serious about being a primecontractor,&quot; said Keith Belton, director of Automation Planning Services atthe Yankee Group, a market research company in Boston.andP;  &quot;The danger that DECfaces is in competing with third parties--they beat out Hewlett-Packard andIBM in the Boeing deal.&quot;andM;Echoing the view of a Yankee Group study called &quot;Systems Integration: AMarket Perspective,&quot; Belton voiced doubts about the future growth of the SImarket.andM;&quot;I disagree with the assumption that the integration market is growing byleaps and bounds,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;It's self-liquidating--there are tools thatwill do the job that the integrators are doing.andM;&quot;If integration is linking IBM systems with VAXes, sure the market willincrease,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;If you're talking about linking application software,it will continue, but four or five years down the road there will be tools toconfigure common data definitions and dictionaries and file formats that willeliminate [the need].&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>